  {
    "title": "Grants, Loans to Support Water Infrastructure, Diamond Says",
    "url": "http://www.RepDiamond.com/News/38302/Press-Releases/Grants--Loans-to-Support-Water-Infrastructure--Diamond-Says",
    "date": null,
    "raw_text": "Grants, Loans to Support Water Infrastructure, Diamond Says\nJuly 15, 2026\nHARRISBURG – More than $12 million in state funding will support two water infrastructure projects affecting people who live and work in the 102nd District, according to Rep. Russ Diamond (R-Lebanon).\n“Access to safe, clean drinking water is part of what makes Pennsylvania communities appealing to long-term residents and newcomers alike. This funding will help the local municipal authorities provide that key service while doing so without overburdening taxpayers and water customers,” he said.\nThe Fredericksburg Sewer and Water Authority will receive a grant of more than $6.4 million and a low-interest loan of nearly $4.6 million to construct a centralized water filtration plant at the site of a decommissioned wastewater treatment facility. The project will improve system reliability and reduce manganese contamination in the water supply.\nThe Womelsdorf-Robesonia Joint Authority was awarded a low-interest loan of nearly $1.2 million to rehabilitate the Furnace Creek water storage tank, which has reached the end of its service life. Improvements include cleaning and recoating the tank, repairing deteriorated welds, replacing the roof vent and mesh screen, and completing additional upgrades to prevent leaks. The project will help maintain reliable water service and fire protection for area residents.\n“Reliable water service is a critical piece of building strong, vibrant communities,” said Sen. Chris Gebhard (R-Lebanon/Berks/Lancaster). “Ensuring our infrastructure is operational is a key function of government, and I’m pleased this funding is dedicated to that purpose.”\nThe funding was approved through the Pennsylvania Infrastructure Investment Authority (PENNVEST), which provides low-cost financial assistance for projects that improve drinking water, wastewater and stormwater infrastructure while protecting public health, supporting environmental stewardship and promoting economic development.\nRepresentative Russ Diamond\n102nd  District\nPennsylvania House of Representatives\nMedia Contact: Jennifer Fitch\n717.260.6563\njfitch@pahousegop.com\nRepDiamond.com\nShare\nSign Up to Receive Legislative Email Updates\nKeep up-to-date on the latest legislative and community news. Your email address will be used strictly for legislative purposes.\nEmail*\nZIP Code\nSubscribe",
    "ai_summary": {
      "summary": "Pennsylvania's PENNVEST program approved over $12 million in grants and low-interest loans for two water infrastructure projects in Lebanon County. The Fredericksburg Sewer and Water Authority received approximately $11 million to build a new water filtration plant, and the Womelsdorf-Robesonia Joint Authority received nearly $1.2 million to repair an aging water storage tank. Rep. Diamond announced the funding but did not introduce legislation; the awards were made through an existing state financing authority.",
      "action_type": "statement",
      "topics": [
        "infrastructure",
        "environment",
        "public_safety"
      ],
      "spin_flag": true
    }
  },
